<br>
In part one I discussed raid roles for the various classes and the necessety of balanceing groups.  In this section I will attempt to cover the remaining items: Main group, healing and pulling.<br>
<br>
MAIN GROUP<br>
<br>
In the main group I try and place the highest level representatives of each catigory.  For example: In the Hole raid last weekend the main group consisted of Shevia (lv 60+ monk puller), Sarpassta (56 sk tank), Coeda (lv 63 cleric healer), Tokaaz (lv60 shammy slower/haster), VonAlbrecht (lv 56 ranger dps and aggro control) and Phunani (lv 53 druid secondary healer and zone necessary).  Shevia was the highest level monk present and was the best choice for puller at the begining of the raid.  When she left the raid I replaced her with Murs who was my second choice for puller because he was the second highest level monk.  Both Sarpassta and VonAlbrecht are the same level (being the highest level melee in the raid) and I chose Sarpassta as Main Aggro because of the difference in the Plate ac vs Chain ac.  Coeda and Tokaaz were also in the main group because they were the highest level characters of their catigory.  Phunani was not the highest level secondary healer but because of the presence of Tokaaz and the nature of The Hole i considered it important that every group have a porter of some type in their group.  Even when I reorganized groups later I kept either a druid or a wizzy in each group so that we could get out or succor if it was necessary.<br>
<br>
The primary benifit and purpose of the main group is communication.  If the raid leader is in the main group he/she has more control of the raid.  He/she can make requests in group that will be more likely to be noticed than tells and the raid channel.  Mana status, multiple pulls, directions (as in where do we want to go), and buffs can all be said in group and do little to disrupt the rest of the raid.  I have worked with the main puller outside the main group.  Useing tells is nowhere near as effective as grouping with him.<br>
<br>
If the raid is large enough or complex enough(ex the plate cycle in kael) to warrant a Secondary Group the same general rules apply.  The only difference would be that members of the Main group are outside of consideration for the secondary group.<br>
<br>
HEALING/BUFFING<br>
<br>
Some situations require more than &quot;inc complete heal on MT&quot;.  There are mobs out there that can take down a tank in less than 30 seconds with him being lv 65 and completely buffed(im thinking Vindi, Tormax, The Dracolich and thats just in velious and fear). I am not going to address this too much because my cleric is only lv 28 and I have no experience in this area.  I have seen multiple clerics &quot;chain heal&quot; a tank when going up against a hard mob and they were highly coordinated.  Not only were the clerics (i believe there were 4) highly coordinated but the line of tanks was clearly delineated and we were down to the 3rd tank when the mob finaly went down.  I will just emphasize healing is  incredibly important and ask one of our senior clerics to fill in this blank.<br>
<br>
PULLING<br>
<br>
Pulling is just as important as any of the other considerations in a raid.  Splitting mobs and single pulls can be the difference between getting a drop and being wiped out.  Again in this instance I do not have a monk/sk/necro/bard who can split mobs and who is asked to pull in raids.  I will bow to the more experienced pullers in the game and will ask some of our senior pullers to add their comments here.<br>
<br>
Ok guys thats a wrap for now.  Please comment and ask questions.  I have made an attempt at outlineing the basics of running a raid but there is always room for improvement and comments.<br>
<br>
Thank You<br>
