<br>
Von makes so very good points in his discussions. Growing up as a low level toon you begin to learn your role as a specialized toon and not just caster or mellee. It took me a while and so odd things to happen before I was able to truely grasp how &quot;real raiding&quot; works. Let me explain a bit. For me there is a difference in super grouping and raiding. Raiding usually requires more than one group to kill the mob no matter what level they are. While supergrouping can get a lot accomplished, usually there is little definition in leadership and roles, basicaly because the goals are to kill lots of mobs. What can make supergrouping successful is using raid ideals. Ideals are those like Von mentioned. In many of the raids I have attended there were channels for clerics, nukers, and raid leaders. A key to successful raiding is having the trust of those attending. Hot keys or macros advising engage or other important commands are a must. <br>
<br>
Mellee should know a few things to help the raid as a unit. IMO these apply to all except in the main tanking line. Weapons that do not proc aggro detraction should be used. Bash should also be avoided as it is an aggro attractant. Two handed weapons are typically preferred because you can stand farther back from the mob and still hit it. In fact, you should approach mobs by assisting the MT with a hotkey and walk to the mob until your chat window displayes your contacts. There are a few reasons for this, one is to allow those with shorter weapons the ability to make hits on the mob, but also to avoid AE and flurries. There should be a hot key made to spam when a mob rampages advising folks to back off. During rampage the only engangement of the mob should be by the Rampage tank and the Main Tank. The reason for this is simple, the clerics are all concentrating on healing the MT and don't have the extra time to cast heals on others who had no business getting hit to begin with. One last thing is to back off if you have aggro! Again clerics are concerned with keeping one person alive, if the MT drops mobs go wild and it become difficult for the secondary tank to regain aggro before too many are dropped. <br>
<br>
For clerics - the hardest working class in the game. So, you have sat one your pretty little tushes your whole life and popped up to cast a heal then back down. Guess what, thats all over in raids! The prime requisite is the ability to count to 8!!!!! WHen it comes to raiding clerics must know how to make hot keys, open chat channels and program key casted spells. The mouse can fail or slide if you are in a hurry to click a spell off and the raid needs to know you are on time with your casting of spells. In many cases a minimuim of 4 clerics are needed for the chain heals. It takes 8 seconds for Complete Heal to be cast so make sure you program your hot key for raid say and the cleric channel. You will be in a certain oder so be sure you know what it is. If someone link dies in the chain you need to pick up the slack. Also make sure you are at your maximum casting range, the raid doesn't need you dying to the mobs AE and flurries. In most castes the group is not your concern, just the MT. Some exceptions include the poison AE of Trak where your group heal spells are needed. <br>
<br>
Allanone makes a good point, in making your group leaders someone who has had some raiding exp or someone who you can communicate well with. Party members should direct their communications and questions to the group leader and the group leader can then act upon. Some instances are when a group missed a buff, there is no need for 6 raid spams that my group missed it, a tell from the group leader to the caster fixes it and doesn't interupt raid comments. Raid say is needed for raid comments, a channel to important facts about actions theat have or need to happen, keeping it clear of unneeded chat is important. <br>
<br>
Some key information for all users is to listen/read all comments. If you are asked to do something odd, chances are it is for a good reason. If you have never raided a particular mob, then you may not understand why, but chances are by the end of the battle and noone is lost you will understand. What do I mean? In Fear you may be told before the encounter with Cazic to drop all your buffs!!! The reason is this mob dispells and you need to have certain buffs on at the end in mopes of succeeding. When fighting Ictus Viterus (sorry on spelling) Staying behind his throne in pre stage keeps aggro away and also mellee should fight him with thier backs to the throne as he pushes you way away casuing you to aggro others, if you do just die! When fighting Trak casters and then others who can fit should be under him to avoid the AE. <br>
<br>
There's many more than this and these are just my opinions and observations from my experiences and raids I have attended. But I hope these help future raid leaders and members gain an idea of what will be expected of them and how important their role is. <br>
